          <avActivityHighlights>In some localities increase in avalanche danger as a consequence of warming during the day and solar radiation.</avActivityHighlights>
          <avActivityComment>During the day: In steep rocky terrain and on sunny slopes small and medium-sized moist avalanches are possible as a consequence of warming during the day and solar radiation. &lt;br/&gt; Especially adjacent to ridgelines and in gullies and bowls: The fresh snow of Sunday as well as the scattered wind slabs can be released by a single winter sport participant. This applies in particular on very steep shady slopes. &lt;br/&gt; Backcountry touring calls for caution.</avActivityComment>
          <snowpackStructureComment>10 to 30 cm of snow, and up to 50 cm in some localities, fell on Sunday. Especially in the areas bordering Piedmont. Where it is gradually settling down. Down to 900 m snow has fallen since Sunday in some localities. The wind was light to moderate adjacent to ridgelines. &lt;br/&gt; &lt;br/&gt; In some places new snow is lying on the soft surface of an old snowpack. Or on crusts. &lt;br/&gt; Towards its surface, the snowpack is soft and has a loosely bonded surface. Weak layers exist in the snowpack in particular on steep shady slopes. &lt;br/&gt; Especially adjacent to ridgelines in all aspects: Over a wide area snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind.</snowpackStructureComment>
          <tendencyComment>The weather will be cold. Strong northerly wind: The avalanche danger will increase during the day.</tendencyComment>
